'''Leigh Mercer''' (1893–1977) was a noted [[British people|British]] [[wordplay]] and [[recreational mathematics]] expert.<ref>A. Ross Eckler: ''Leigh Mercer, Palindromist.'' In: ''Word Ways.'' Volume 24, Issue 3, 1991, Article 2, p. 131–138 [https://digitalcommons.butler.edu/wordways/vol24/iss3/2/]</ref> He is best known for devising the celebrated [[palindrome]] "[[Panama Canal|A man, a plan, a canal — Panama!]]".<ref name="MercerPanama">Published in ''Notes and Queries,'' 13 Nov. 1948, according to ''The Yale Book of Quotations,'' F. R. Shapiro, ed. (2006, {{ISBN|0-300-10798-6}}).</ref>
The following [[mathematical joke|mathematical limerick]] is attributed to him:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lhup.edu/~DSIMANEK/mayhem.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008070848/www.lhup.edu/~DSIMANEK/mayhem.htm| archive-date=2017-10-08|title=Math Mayhem |publisher=Lhup.edu |accessdate=2011-06-29}}</ref> :<math> \frac{12 + 144 + 20 + 3 \sqrt{4}}{7} + (5 \times 11) = 9^2+0</math> This is read as follows: : A [[dozen]], a [[Gross (unit)|gross]], and a [[20 (number)|score]] : Plus three times the square root of four : Divided by seven : Plus five times eleven : Is nine squared and not a bit more.
==References== {{reflist}}
