{{more citations needed|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox television | show_name = Lock n' Load with R. Lee Ermey | image = LockNLoadDVDCover.jpg | caption = ''Lock N' Load with R. Lee Ermey'' DVD cover | show_name_2 = Lock n' Load | genre = [[Reality television]] | creator = | developer = | writer = | director = | creative_director = | presenter = | starring = [[R. Lee Ermey]] | judges = | voices = | narrated = | theme_music_composer = | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = | language = English | num_seasons = 1 | num_episodes = 13 | list_episodes = | executive_producer = | producer = | editor = | location = | cinematography = | camera = | company = | distributor = | channel = [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History]] | picture_format = | audio_format = | first_run = | first_aired = {{start date|2009|07|26}} | last_aired = {{end date|2009|11|13}} | status = | runtime = 44 minutes | preceded_by = | followed_by = | related = | website = https://web.archive.org/web/20091008233623/http://www.history.com/video.do?name=LockNLoad | production_website = }}
'''''Lock n' Load with R. Lee Ermey''''' is a reality television series about the development of military weaponry throughout the centuries. Hosted by actor and former [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] [[drill instructor]] [[R. Lee Ermey]], its one season originally aired on the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History]] channel in 2009.
==Format== In a typical episode, Ermey focused on one specific type of weapon or weapon system, presenting key advancements in its technology and demonstrating their use with the help of experts. In a holdover from his duties hosting ''[[Mail Call]]'' on the History Channel, he frequently added humor in the form of light-hearted [[drill instructor]] haranguing aimed at the viewer. He also displayed an eagerness to try out the episode's relevant weapons against a wide range of targets, particularly [[watermelon]]s ("they taste better after being shot with a machine gun"), as well as glass bottles.
The pilot episode was produced by Simon J. Heath, who also developed the concept.
==Episodes==
The pilot episode first aired in December 2008. This rated well and was followed by a series in 2009. The show premiered on July 26, 2009 and only ran for one season and ended up getting cancelled in November 2009.<ref name=IMDbEpisodes/>
#"[[Artillery]]" #"[[Machine Gun]]s" #"[[Tank]]s" #"[[Handgun|Pistols]]" #"[[Helicopter]]s" (filmed at Yakima Firing Center in Yakima, Washington) #"[[Armored personnel carrier|Armored Vehicles]]" #"[[Shotgun]]s" #"[[Rocket]]s" #"[[Blade]]s" #"[[Ammunition|Ammo]]" #"[[Rifles]]" #"MG2" (Machine Guns, part 2) #"Bunker Busters" (military [[demolition]])
